Japan's Sega Enterprises Ltd. plans to start  providing video game software to homes, using cable television networks, a  newspaper said Sunday.
The unique service enabling people to play computer games at home will  begin in the United States this month and in Japan next month, the Asahi  Shimbun newspaper said.
Users can enjoy various types of video games for about 3,000 yen (29  dollars) a month on the system developed by the major Japanese computer game  maker, it said.
